2. obviam mihi: cf. Cicero's account of his reception on return- ing from exile in Ep. XV. 5.- mederi: Cicero's absence from Italy while civil war was brewing, his absence from the senate dur- ing the stormy debates of the first week in January, as well as his well-known opportunism in poli- tics, and his friendly relations with both Caesar and Pompey, seemed to make him the natural mediator between the opposing factions. That he hoped to effect a com- promise is clear from many re- marks in the Letters (cf.‚ eg„ Ep. LXV. 5). What many condemn as cowardice in his course during the Civil War finds at least partial justification in his desire to keep a neutral attitude‚ which would enable him to negotiate a peace. —— ex utraque parte : among others Cicero is thinking of the Pompeians Scipio and Lentulus, and the Caesarians Antony and Cassius; cf. Caes. B. C. 1. 1-4‚ and see Ep. LXV. 6 victa est, etc.— minacis . . . litteras: the letter read by Curio in the senate Jan. 1 (see introd. note). Caesar (B. C. 1.
